							<p>Ahmadi Mahmood Jan is surviving in the Jungle to keep his dream of returning to London alive.</p>
<p>The 21-year-old, who claims he worked as a mechanic for US troops before fleeing war-torn Afghanistan, was deported from the UK to Italy a month ago.</p>
<p>Now he is living in a small makeshift tent in the sprawling migrant camp that has sprung up on the eastern outskirts of Calais, hoping he can find a way back.</p>
<p><!-- WP Tag START -->
<!-- vid:  http://delivery.vidible.tv/video/redirect/55ba7ff7e4b02f07491428a4?bcid=538612f0e4b00fbb8e898655&w=640&h=360 -->

<div class="vdb_player vdb_55ba8071e4b046371921dfd6538612f0e4b00fbb8e898655">
    <script type="text/javascript" src="//delivery.vidible.tv/jsonp/pid=55ba8071e4b046371921dfd6/vid=55ba7ff7e4b02f07491428a4/538612f0e4b00fbb8e898655.js"></script>
</div>

<!-- WP Tag END --></p>
<p>His journey first began five years ago when he decided that his work for the Americans had made him a marked man in his native Nangarhar province.</p>
<p>He walked over the border to Iran before moving on to Turkey, Greece, Italy, Belgium, France and finally England.</p>
<p>Ahmadi lost his mother when he was born and is not sure whether his father is dead or alive. He has a sister, but has lost contact with her and is unsure where she is living.</p>
<figure><img src="http://snappa.static.pressassociation.io/assets/2015/07/30171407/1438272845-6d7ea81db9d6207601f624a8ae34d611-600x388.jpg" alt="shelters in the migrant camp known as the new Jungle in Calais, France" /><figcaption>(Yui Mok/PA)</figcaption></figure></p>
<p>Arriving in London, he found work in a butcher&#8217;s in Brixton Market, in the south of the capital, and people there treated him &#8220;like a son&#8221;.</p>
<p>He told the Press Association: &#8220;I have dear friends in Brixton, a lot of English people, they are like my family. They call me all the time but I can&#8217;t go there.</p>
<p>&#8220;In England you get everything easily. Here in Europe I can go everywhere because I have refugee document for three years. But I don&#8217;t get job or school in Europe, just in England.&#8221;</p>
<figure><img src="http://snappa.static.pressassociation.io/assets/2015/07/30171322/1438272800-3022aaed84aa61df35a83ef68b2bac6c-600x413.jpg" alt="Graffiti on the walls of an underpass near the entrance to the migrant camp known as the new Jungle in Calais, France." /><figcaption>(Yui Mok/PA)</figcaption></figure></p>
<p>Ahmadi says that a month ago the UK Border Agency informed him he was being deported to Italy, where he first obtained refugee status.</p>
<p>He was taken to a police station and identified before ending up in the Dover Immigration Removal Centre to await a flight to Rome.</p>
<p>&#8220;It&#8217;s a prison,&#8221; he said of the complex located in Dover&#8217;s historic citadel in the town&#8217;s Western Heights fortifications.</p>
<figure><img src="http://snappa.static.pressassociation.io/assets/2015/07/30170823/1438272502-9a04f0dfdee48687a80cd05968e83aae-600x337.jpg" alt="Ahmadi Mahmood Jan" /><figcaption>(Angus Dunsire/PA)</figcaption></figure></p>
<p>&#8220;At 8pm they close the door and you can&#8217;t go out. Just in a small room two persons, it&#8217;s small like my tent, for 12 hours.&#8221;</p>
<p>But none of the hardships have stopped him from hoping he can return to England.</p>
<p>Since making his way back to France he has tried four times to get on to a train or a lorry at the freight terminal in Coquelles. &#8220;I am going to keep trying, I have to keep trying,&#8221; he said.</p>
<script type="text/javascript"><!--
